No, Agnosticism is the idea that one can't have knowledge of God's existence so can neither affirm or deny that god exists. I know there are no instances of various concepts of god, because they are absurd logically. For instance, the concept of a god that is supremely good, all knowing, and all powerful leads to many logical contradictions. I know such a concept can't have any instances in the world just as I know there is no such thing as a &quot;round-square&quot;.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Well of course, but that's assuming that the only definition of a god is &quot;a purely good, omniscient, omnipresent entity.&quot;<br>
<br>
You know, even if there is a &quot;higher being&quot; of some sort (even if not omnipotent, since it is impossible)—and this was a very interesting concept to me when I first realized it—even if there is a god, nothing says that he must be <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> good</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. Have you ever considered that one?<br>
<br>
Read <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>Job: A Comedy of Justice</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> by Robert A. Heinlein sometime. It gives you a very different perspective on the whole thing, lol. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/umuzaak.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Muzaak</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_lightning.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 59<br> <font color=#E9D756>(10/14/01 10:14:40 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=138.topic&index=244>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Do you believe in god?</span><hr size=1> Quote Triff:<br>
<br>
&quot;Well of course, but that's assuming that the only definition of a god is 'a purely good, omniscient, omnipresent entity.' &quot;<br>
<br>
I was making a general statement with regard to any concept of god that contains contradictions. There can be no instances of a concept that leads to a logical absurdity.<br>
<br>
Quote Triff:<br>
<br>
&quot;You know, even if there is a &quot;higher being&quot; of some sort (even if not omnipotent, since it is impossible)—and this was a very interesting concept to me when I first realized it—even if there is a god, nothing says that he must be good. Have you ever considered that one?&quot;<br>
<br>
Interesting point you bring up. Early monotheists (such as Zarathustra, founder of Zoroastrianism) regarded god as both perfectly good and evil. However, the problem is one of definition. How do we measure what is &quot;perfectly&quot; good and evil? We enter into a wide circular argument when we begin to define god(s) in order to help lift arguments which may demonstrate its existence. Theists are at once commited to their definitions and descriptions of god, but when pressed as to how they arrived to the definition they ultimately have to respond that god revealed its nature to them through some means such as &quot;nature&quot;. I am not convinced that there is such a thing as &quot;revelatory truth&quot;. So the short of it, Triff, is that we can bring in all the concepts of god(s) one wants, but in the end how one arrives to the concept is through question begging and &quot;revelatory truth&quot;. In either case I find nothing convincing enough to warrant belief.<br>
